00:00:45.380 --> 00:00:47.430
OK so what I want to
do is finish up

00:00:47.430 --> 00:00:48.760
thinking about circuits.

00:00:48.760 --> 00:00:51.900
And just to get you thinking
about circuits, let's think

00:00:51.900 --> 00:00:52.770
about where we are.

00:00:52.770 --> 00:00:56.840
Last time we saw that one of the
issues in thinking about

00:00:56.840 --> 00:01:02.380
circuit design, is the fact that
every part, in principle,

00:01:02.380 --> 00:01:04.040
interacts with every
other part.

00:01:04.040 --> 00:01:09.210
Which makes the design process
harder than the design process

00:01:09.210 --> 00:01:11.580
was for things like linear
systems, where we thought

00:01:11.580 --> 00:01:15.240
about boxes having inputs
and outputs.

00:01:15.240 --> 00:01:17.300
In linear systems, when we
thought about boxes having

00:01:17.300 --> 00:01:21.260
inputs and outputs, the output
didn't necessarily have any

00:01:21.260 --> 00:01:23.230
affect on the input,
unless there was an

00:01:23.230 --> 00:01:26.490
explicit path feedback.

00:01:26.490 --> 00:01:28.830
In circuits, there's
feedback always.

00:01:28.830 --> 00:01:31.070
There's no way to avoid it.

00:01:31.070 --> 00:01:33.320
And in fact, that coupling can
make thinking about the

00:01:33.320 --> 00:01:35.380
circuits very difficult.

00:01:35.380 --> 00:01:38.530
And we introduce that idea by
just thinking about, even if

00:01:38.530 --> 00:01:41.110
you wanted to close a switch,
you know a circuit, that's

00:01:41.110 --> 00:01:44.760
logically the same as
adding a new part.

00:01:44.760 --> 00:01:47.050
And when you do that, that's
going to change the currents

00:01:47.050 --> 00:01:49.320
and voltages everywhere.

00:01:49.320 --> 00:01:51.250
So that's kind of a big thing--
that's kind of the

00:01:51.250 --> 00:01:55.500
thing that's different about
circuits from what we've been

00:01:55.500 --> 00:01:56.750
thinking about before.

00:01:59.050 --> 00:02:01.330
Because that complicates design,
we'd like some way of

00:02:01.330 --> 00:02:02.110
dealing with it.

00:02:02.110 --> 00:02:04.850
And the way we introduced, and
the way that you used in the

00:02:04.850 --> 00:02:07.280
lab, so far, has been
to use a buffer.

00:02:07.280 --> 00:02:09.620
We can use an op-amp
to make a buffer.

00:02:09.620 --> 00:02:13.480
And a buffer has this nice
isolation property.

00:02:13.480 --> 00:02:16.010
In this particular circuit, it
has the property that it

00:02:16.010 --> 00:02:18.820
copies this voltage to the
output, regardless of what's

00:02:18.820 --> 00:02:20.070
at the output.

00:02:22.170 --> 00:02:24.340
That means we could put a switch
here, we could change

00:02:24.340 --> 00:02:26.760
the light bulb, we could do
anything we wanted to, and we

00:02:26.760 --> 00:02:30.190
would still know, because of the
properties of the op-amp,

00:02:30.190 --> 00:02:32.677
we would still know that this
voltage is going to be 8

00:02:32.677 --> 00:02:34.730
Volts, regardless of
what we put there.

00:02:34.730 --> 00:02:36.890
So that's very nice, that gives
us a modularity, that

00:02:36.890 --> 00:02:39.600
gives us a way to
design things.

00:02:39.600 --> 00:02:41.990
It let's us design the left--

00:02:41.990 --> 00:02:44.580
make a circuit that generates
8 Volts without knowing

00:02:44.580 --> 00:02:48.030
precisely what's going
to be the ultimate

00:02:48.030 --> 00:02:49.820
circuit that that drives.

00:02:49.820 --> 00:02:53.910
So that's nice, it allows
us to do modularity.

00:02:53.910 --> 00:02:57.650
And in many instances, that's
a very good solution.

00:02:57.650 --> 00:02:59.310
In fact in the solution-- in
the problems that you are

00:02:59.310 --> 00:03:00.320
working on in lab, where you're

00:03:00.320 --> 00:03:03.280
trying to drive a motor--

00:03:03.280 --> 00:03:06.710
that's an excellent solution.

00:03:06.710 --> 00:03:09.200
It's not always an excellent
solution.

00:03:09.200 --> 00:03:12.590
In some sense, it's
very expensive.

00:03:12.590 --> 00:03:15.620
An op-amp is a complicated
part.

00:03:15.620 --> 00:03:19.860
If you were to look inside an
op-amp, there's some two dozen

00:03:19.860 --> 00:03:22.470
transistors in most op-amps.

00:03:22.470 --> 00:03:25.190
So it's not an inexpensive
part, especially when you

00:03:25.190 --> 00:03:27.310
think about this kind of a
circuit that only has three

00:03:27.310 --> 00:03:28.770
parts to the left.

00:03:28.770 --> 00:03:33.110
The op-amp is actually a more
complex device than

00:03:33.110 --> 00:03:35.370
anything else up.

00:03:35.370 --> 00:03:38.700
So op-amps are wonderful,
op-amps allow us to make

00:03:38.700 --> 00:03:41.060
buffers, buffers are wonderful,
but they're not

00:03:41.060 --> 00:03:44.540
always the best solution for
thinking about modularity.

00:03:44.540 --> 00:03:46.940
And, in fact, there's
other ways.

00:03:46.940 --> 00:03:49.020
And so that's what we want to
think about today is -- other

00:03:49.020 --> 00:03:55.800
ways for achieving modularity
in circuit design.

00:03:55.800 --> 00:03:59.830
And the key to thinking about
this, is to think about, well,

00:03:59.830 --> 00:04:02.540
what's the worst thing
that could happen?

00:04:02.540 --> 00:04:08.440
If I changed this part
arbitrarily, just how bad can

00:04:08.440 --> 00:04:09.690
