00:11:28.910 --> 00:11:31.370
It's not very hard.

00:11:31.370 --> 00:11:35.306
AUDIENCE: The voltages drop out
of the [UNINTELLIGIBLE].

00:11:35.306 --> 00:11:37.790
The resistor has to be
the same as the--

00:11:37.790 --> 00:11:39.330
PROFESSOR: So the voltages--

00:11:39.330 --> 00:11:40.300
that's an instance--

00:11:40.300 --> 00:11:43.310
what you just said-- is
an instance of KVL.

00:11:43.310 --> 00:11:46.360
Basically, the voltage around
all of the loops better be 0.

00:11:46.360 --> 00:11:48.550
The sum of the voltages around
all of the loops better be 0,

00:11:48.550 --> 00:11:51.290
and the sum of the currents in
all of those closed surfaces

00:11:51.290 --> 00:11:52.250
better be 0, right?

00:11:52.250 --> 00:11:55.540
KVL better be satisfied
everywhere, and KCL better be

00:11:55.540 --> 00:11:57.240
satisfied everywhere.

00:11:57.240 --> 00:11:59.740
So, in particular, we can
ask about this node.

00:11:59.740 --> 00:12:01.660
We could say, do the currents
flowing into

00:12:01.660 --> 00:12:05.580
that node sum to 0?

00:12:05.580 --> 00:12:08.560
So if you take a line here--
let's take this line--

00:12:08.560 --> 00:12:10.710
if V0 happened to be--

00:12:10.710 --> 00:12:14.070
V0 happens to be the voltage
here, right?

00:12:14.070 --> 00:12:19.730
So if V0 were 36, then that puts
some voltage on this leg.

00:12:19.730 --> 00:12:21.353
36 would what, 54?

00:12:24.490 --> 00:12:26.500
So then you'd have to say--

00:12:26.500 --> 00:12:28.420
you'd have to compute, then, the
current through here and

00:12:28.420 --> 00:12:30.410
the current through there,
and see if those

00:12:30.410 --> 00:12:32.790
currents sum to 0.

00:12:32.790 --> 00:12:36.890
And, in fact, if you do those
calculations, you if you can

00:12:36.890 --> 00:12:38.830
convince yourself of
those are all true.

00:12:38.830 --> 00:12:40.690
So the answer was 0.

00:12:40.690 --> 00:12:43.640
All of those answers
were true.

00:12:43.640 --> 00:12:46.320
The point of doing the exercise
was to just remind

00:12:46.320 --> 00:12:50.260
you about how you solve
circuits, but also to let us

00:12:50.260 --> 00:12:53.090
look at patterns.

00:12:53.090 --> 00:12:55.650
The interesting thing in this
problem is the pattern the

00:12:55.650 --> 00:13:00.140
results between the
V's and the I's.

00:13:00.140 --> 00:13:06.290
So if I were to make a plot, in
fact, those V's and I's all

00:13:06.290 --> 00:13:09.180
fall on a straight line.

00:13:09.180 --> 00:13:12.400
Well that's pretty
interesting.

00:13:12.400 --> 00:13:17.720
So if I plot just this
V versus this I--

00:13:17.720 --> 00:13:19.974
so V equals 0, 30, 36,
0, 30, 36, 48, 60 --

00:13:23.970 --> 00:13:26.380
and the corresponding
I's, 30,15,12,6,0 --

00:13:26.380 --> 00:13:29.360
30,15,12,6,0.

00:13:29.360 --> 00:13:33.190
Those points all fall
on a straight line.

00:13:33.190 --> 00:13:36.820
That suggests that there's
some pattern here.

00:13:36.820 --> 00:13:39.630
And if there's a pattern, then
there might be a way to

00:13:39.630 --> 00:13:40.730
exploit it.

00:13:40.730 --> 00:13:42.720
So that's what I'm trying
to develop--

00:13:42.720 --> 00:13:46.840
is a way to exploit the pattern
that results when

00:13:46.840 --> 00:13:50.470
parts of circuits interact.

00:13:50.470 --> 00:13:52.180
The interesting thing
that we--

00:13:52.180 --> 00:13:55.160
so not only is it true that
there's a simple pattern, but

00:13:55.160 --> 00:13:59.370
it turns out that the pattern
is completely independent of

00:13:59.370 --> 00:14:02.003
the thing that I put
on the right.

00:14:02.003 --> 00:14:06.165
The pattern is a property of
the circuit to the left.

00:14:08.960 --> 00:14:12.170
One way to convince yourself
of that is to substitute--

00:14:12.170 --> 00:14:17.120
take that resistor out, and put
in a voltage source, and

00:14:17.120 --> 00:14:19.540
redo the problem.

00:14:19.540 --> 00:14:23.180
This time, instead of assuming
that there's an Ohm's Law-type

00:14:23.180 --> 00:14:26.120
resistor here, assume there's
a constant voltage, and that

00:14:26.120 --> 00:14:30.410
constant voltage is adjusted
to 0,30,36,48,60.

00:14:30.410 --> 00:14:32.600
If you re-solve that
problem, you get

00:14:32.600 --> 00:14:35.930
exactly these same currents.

00:14:35.930 --> 00:14:41.710
The answer continues to fall
on exactly the same line.

00:14:41.710 --> 00:14:43.270
So that's a very interesting
pattern.

00:14:43.270 --> 00:14:46.800
The idea is that when the
circuit on the left interacts

00:14:46.800 --> 00:14:49.430
with the circuit on the right,
regardless of what the circuit

00:14:49.430 --> 00:14:53.490
on the right is, you get a
simple relationship between

00:14:53.490 --> 00:14:55.730
the voltage and current
that comes out of the

00:14:55.730 --> 00:14:56.980
circuit on the left.

00:14:59.570 --> 00:15:02.510
So that motivates the idea that
we can think about the

00:15:02.510 --> 00:15:09.260
left-hand circuit as some
kind of a generic part.

00:15:09.260 --> 00:15:12.490
We call that generic
part a one-port.

00:15:12.490 --> 00:15:14.750
Think about this circuit on the
left-- the thing that's in

00:15:14.750 --> 00:15:17.100
the red box--

00:15:17.100 --> 00:15:19.120
it's got at its terminals--

00:15:19.120 --> 00:15:22.490
the terminals are the things
that poke through the red box.

00:15:22.490 --> 00:15:24.530
First off it has two terminals,
two terminals is

00:15:24.530 --> 00:15:26.760
just like all of our
other parts.

00:15:26.760 --> 00:15:29.020
And it's like a resistor, it's
like a voltage source, it's

00:15:29.020 --> 00:15:33.800
like a current source, it's
a two terminal device.

00:15:33.800 --> 00:15:36.460
And just like a voltage source
or a resistor or a current

00:15:36.460 --> 00:15:39.480
source, there's some voltage
across those terminals, and

00:15:39.480 --> 00:15:43.470
there's some current that flows
in those terminals.

00:15:43.470 --> 00:15:45.170
So there's some current
that goes in the plus.

00:15:45.170 --> 00:15:47.210
And that same current
comes out the minus.

00:15:47.210 --> 00:15:50.080
That'll be true for this
circuit, just the same as it's

00:15:50.080 --> 00:15:53.780
true for a resistor or voltage
source or anything else, the

00:15:53.780 --> 00:15:57.580
only difference is, the thing
that's inside the box--

00:15:57.580 --> 00:15:59.100
the thing that's inside
the one-port--

00:15:59.100 --> 00:16:03.510
is more complicated than it was
for a simple resistor or

00:16:03.510 --> 00:16:05.080
voltage source or
current source.

00:16:05.080 --> 00:16:08.550
So what we can think about, is
this whole red box just looks

00:16:08.550 --> 00:16:12.320
like a super part.

00:16:12.320 --> 00:16:16.700
So the interesting thing that
happens is, this red box

00:16:16.700 --> 00:16:20.300
behaves like a one-port,
like a super part.

00:16:20.300 --> 00:16:25.510
And just like a resistor has a
relationship between V and I,

00:16:25.510 --> 00:16:29.610
V equals IR, Or a voltage source
has some kind of a

00:16:29.610 --> 00:16:32.520
constraint, V equals V0.

00:16:32.520 --> 00:16:34.250
Or a current source
has some kind of a

00:16:34.250 --> 00:16:36.460
constraint, I equals I0.

00:16:36.460 --> 00:16:40.740
This funny part has a
relationship between V and I

00:16:40.740 --> 00:16:43.340
that's given by that curve.

00:16:43.340 --> 00:16:47.180
In some sense, it's not
very different.

00:16:47.180 --> 00:16:48.510
So we think that--

00:16:48.510 --> 00:16:52.960
so what we want to do now is
figure out the rules that

00:16:52.960 --> 00:16:54.780
govern the currents
and voltages that

00:16:54.780 --> 00:16:56.030
flow through one-ports.

00:16:58.270 --> 00:17:03.900
And in particular, how special
was this straight line thing?

00:17:03.900 --> 00:17:05.990
I mean if they were always a
